# .cursorrules — Go
# Kept in sync with CLAUDE.md. These rules override default Cursor behavior.

You are working in a Go (latest stable) project. Standard library first; modules via go.mod.

## Scope discipline
- Change only what the task requires. Do NOT refactor, rename, or reformat unrelated code.
- Prefer the standard library; ask before adding a dependency — every module is a supply-chain + maintenance cost.
- No speculative generality (YAGNI). No interfaces/generics "for flexibility" before two real implementations exist.

## Errors (Go's core discipline)
- Check EVERY returned error. Never discard with `_` unless justified in a comment.
- Wrap with context: fmt.Errorf("...: %w", err) — a bare `return err` loses the call path.
- Compare with errors.Is/errors.As, NEVER by string matching.
- Do NOT panic for ordinary/expected errors — return them. Reserve panic for unrecoverable programmer bugs.

## Concurrency (the #1 Go production failure mode)
- Every goroutine needs a defined exit path — never start one you can't stop. Tie its lifetime to a context and select on ctx.Done(). A goroutine blocked forever is a memory leak.
- context.Context is the FIRST parameter of any function that does I/O, blocks, or spawns goroutines. Propagate it; respect cancellation; never store it in a struct.
- Guard all shared mutable state (mutex) or confine to one goroutine + channels. Run `go test -race`.
- Use errgroup/sync.WaitGroup to wait for goroutines; don't fire-and-forget.

## API & types
- Accept interfaces, return concrete structs.
- Keep interfaces small and define them where consumed, not where implemented.
- Useful zero values where practical. Doc comments on exported identifiers, starting with the name. Minimal exported surface.

## Dependencies, state, resources
- NO global mutable state — inject dependencies via constructors. Globals make code untestable and create hidden coupling.
- Keep main thin: wire deps, start server, handle shutdown. Logic lives in packages.
- defer Close() every opened resource (files, rows, response bodies, conns) right after checking the open error.
- Handle SIGTERM/SIGINT: cancel root context, drain with a timeout, exit.

## Security
- No hardcoded secrets (env only; committed secrets leak permanently via git history).
- database/sql placeholders ($1/?), NEVER fmt.Sprintf/concatenation for SQL.
- Validate + bound all external input. Set timeouts on every HTTP client and server (ReadTimeout/WriteTimeout) — a missing timeout is a hang/DoS.

## Code style
- gofmt/goimports always. Pass go vet and (if configured) staticcheck/golangci-lint clean.
- Early returns; keep the happy path un-indented. Short names in short scopes, descriptive exported names, no stutter.
- No commented-out code or context-free TODOs.

## Testing & done
- Table-driven tests with t.Run subtests; t.Parallel() where independent; always run with -race. Cover error paths (bad input, cancelled context, downstream failure). Prefer stdlib `testing`.
- Before declaring done: `go build ./...`, `go vet ./...`, `gofmt -l .` (empty), and `go test -race ./...` pass. Every error checked; every goroutine has an exit path; every resource defer-closed; no global mutable state, no hardcoded secrets, no string-built SQL, no panics for ordinary errors. Diff contains only the required change.
